  }, "https://ribbonfarm.com/2014/09/03/how-to-fall-off-the-wagon")), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Self-help ideas generally belong\xA0to one of three schools of thought, whether the originators realize it or not: values-first, goals-first or process-first. "), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "disruptors are\xA0exit\xA0people (leaving a social order is a primary problem-solving technique)"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "reformers are\xA0voice\xA0people (driving reform within a social order is a primary problem-solving technique)"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, mdx("em", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "How to fall off the wagon"), " continuously, and in a circular fashion"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "falling off the wagon is a good thing.\xA0It\u2019s getting back on quickly that\u2019s at the heart of effectiveness. Clinging to one vertex with ferocious tenacity is the pathology.\xA0If you\u2019re not iterating through goals, values and processes continuously, that\u2019s the definition of being stuck."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Goals-first people are idealists. They tend to get fixated\xA0on long-term goals that they are neither able to give up, nor work towards. This is the degeneracy of utopianism. To get unstuck, they need to either get moving (clockwise) or quit (anticlockwise)."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Process-first people are doers. They tend to\xA0get stuck on degenerate processes that have stopped working. \xA0This is the degeneracy of blind ritualism. To get unstuck, they need to either question the process in light of values (clockwise) or break the process in service of goals (anticlockwise) ."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Values-first people are emulators. \xA0They tend to get stuck on identity issues where there is no leader offering a clear model of virtues to emulate. This is the degeneracy of leaderlessness. To get unstuck, they need to either find a\xA0new leader (clockwise) or sacralize\xA0certain new processes, in lieu of a leader (anticlockwise)."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "The interesting case is stuckness: when you fall off a vertex because something derails you, you need to be at one of the other two vertices and are instinctively failing in a particular direction, but keep going back to the comforting home vertex where you were, instead of rolling with the fall towards the next one.\xA0"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Synthesis (improvising a new practice) followed by\u2026\nConflict (between explicit old values and implicit ones in new practice) followed by exit and\u2026\nPrecedent-setting (embodying new values in systematized new practices)."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Hacking is generally a case of overriding insufficient default processes to achieve necessary goals; conflict is generally between the evangelist of the new idea and the priests of the old values who control key assets. Conflict and exit are familiar and dramatic patterns in every disruption story."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Hacker:\xA0Habit-oriented disruptor, breaks things to get something done. They get stuck in chaos."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Non-home vertices and the leg opposite your vertex feel unnatural. Retrograde movement through legs feels even more unnatural. Retrograde movement through the edge opposite your home vertex feels the most unnatural of all."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "If you hate fervent ideological debates, you\u2019re a hacker, your nemesis\xA0is the holy warrior"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Evil twins on the other hand, are those who share your basic orientation (disruption or reform), but are strong where you are weakest: on the path opposite your home vertex. You need them, but hate the fact that you do. \xA0Here\u2019s the evil twins chart. Unlike the nemesis list, it is not symmetric, and your evil twins are on \u201Cyour side\u201D so to speak, in terms of clockwise or anticlockwise handedness."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "The evil twin of the hacker is the contrarian"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "the hacker is the reluctant hero\u2019s tale, who leads a rebellion because nobody else will"), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "Note that 2 and 5 tend to end in tragedy by default, while 1, 3, 4 and 6 tend to end in redemption by default."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "The model is also informed by my fox/hedgehog/cactus/weasel schema. This is much more situated than the Myers-Briggs models, but too poetically ambiguous to be usable in an everyday sense. I\u2019d guess that in my scheme, the legalist and the holy warrior (frenemies at the values vertex) and the investigator (reformer at the process vertex) are hedgehogs. Contrarians, operators and hackers are foxes. The former triad turns into cacti when stuck, while the latter triad turns into weasels when stuck."), mdx("ul", null, mdx("li", {
